Orders and Offers Analysis¶

Data Description¶

We have two data sets: data_orders and data_offers, both being stored in a CSV format. The data_orders data set contains the following columns:

  • order_datetime - time of the order
  • origin_longitude - longitude of the order
  • origin_latitude - latitude of the order
  • m_order_eta - time before order arrival
  • order_gk - order number
  • order_status_key - status, an enumeration consisting of the following mapping:
    • 4 - cancelled by client,
    • 9 - cancelled by system, i.e., a reject
  • is_driver_assigned_key - whether a driver has been assigned
  • cancellation_time_in_seconds - how many seconds passed before cancellation

The data_offers data set is a simple map with 2 columns:

  • order_gk - order number, associated with the same column from the orders data set
  • offer_id - ID of an offer

df_time = df.copy()
In [8]:
# keep only order_gk, m_order_eta, cancellations_time_in_seconds in df_time
df_time = df_time[['order_gk', 'm_order_eta', 'cancellations_time_in_seconds']]
In [9]:
df_time.rename(columns={'order_gk':'order_id', 'm_order_eta': 'eta_in_seconds', 'cancellations_time_in_seconds': 'cancel_in_seconds'}, inplace=True)
In [10]:
# create a new column 'order_status' that contains the order status
df['order_status'] = df['order_status_key'].map({4: 'cancelled_by_client', 9: 'cancelled_by_system'})
df.drop('order_status_key', axis=1, inplace=True)
# create a new column 'order_cancellation_reason' that contains the order cancellation reason
df['is_driver_assigned_key'] = df['is_driver_assigned_key'].map({0: 'No', 1: 'Yes'})
In [11]:
# convert the 'order_datetime', 'm_order_eta', and 'cancellations_time_in_seconds' columns to datetime and timedelta objects
df['order_datetime'] = pd.to_datetime(df['order_datetime'])
df['m_order_eta'] = pd.to_datetime(df['m_order_eta'], unit='s')
df['cancellations_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['cancellations_time_in_seconds'], unit='s')

# drop the 'cancellations_time_in_seconds' column
df.drop('cancellations_time_in_seconds', axis=1, inplace=True)
In [12]:
# transform to datetime format
df['order_time'] = df['order_datetime'].dt.time
df['eta'] = df['m_order_eta'].dt.time
df['cancel'] = df['cancellations_time'].dt.time

# drop the 'order_datetime', 'm_order_eta, 'cancellations_time' columns
df.drop('order_datetime', axis=1, inplace=True)
df.drop('m_order_eta', axis=1, inplace=True)
df.drop('cancellations_time', axis=1, inplace=True)
In [13]:
# create new datetime objects and calculate time differences between columns
df['order_time'] = df['order_time'].apply(lambda x: datetime.combine(datetime.today(), x) if not pd.isna(x) else pd.NaT)
df['eta_time'] = df['order_time'] + df['eta'].apply(lambda x: timedelta(hours=x.hour, minutes=x.minute, seconds=x.second) if not pd.isna(x) else pd.NaT)
df['cancel_time'] = df['eta_time'] + df['cancel'].apply(lambda x: timedelta(hours=x.hour, minutes=x.minute, seconds=x.second) if not pd.isna(x) else pd.NaT)

# use folium to plot the map
m = folium.Map(location=[df['latitude'].mean(), df['longitude'].mean()], zoom_start=10)

# add markers to the map
for index, row in df.iterrows():
    folium.CircleMarker(
        location=[row['latitude'], row['longitude']],
        radius=1,
        color='blue',
        fill=True,
        fill_color='blue'
    ).add_to(m)
